A police officer directs visitors to the U.S. Supreme Court building in 2015.
The headlines say the justices of the Supreme Court are “openly feuding” and “sniping” at one another over the death penalty.
Some opponents of the death penalty wish to see the Supreme Court declare it unconstitutional, and they are not too picky about how that gets done: not jurisprudence but jurispretext.
“Like it or not, the death penalty is constitutional.”The current Supreme Court action regarding the death penalty, from a legal point of view, amounts to little more than trivia.
